\author{eigil-rischel}
\title{Fast-forward functors}
\import{macros}
\taxon{definition}
\p{Fix an interface #{\binom{I}{O}} in the doctrine of discrete-time deterministic dynamical systems (that is, a function of sets #{I \to O}). Recall that #{\cat{Sys}(\binom{I}{O})} is the category of systems with this interface. Let #{n \in \NN} be a natural number. Then there is an endofunctor ##{n \cdot (-) : \cat{Sys}(\binom{I}{O}) \to \cat{Sys}(\binom{I}{O})} defined as follows:}
\p{An object of #{\cat{Sys}(\binom{I}{O})} amounts to a set #{X}, a function #{r: X \to O}, and a function #{u: I \times_O X \to X}. We define #{n \cdot (X,r,u) = (X, r, (i,x) \mapsto (u(i,-)^n)(x))}. (that is, the output is the same, and to update, we apply the update function #{n} times). It is not hard to verify that this is well-defined, and that if #{f: X \to Y} is a homomorphism of systems #{(X,r,u) \to (Y,r',u')}, then it is also a homomorphism #{n(X,r,u) \to n(Y,r',u')}.}